# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: saga-orchestration
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:saga-orchestration/atomicity-database-systems] In database systems, **atomicity** (/ˌætəˈmɪsəti/; from Ancient Greek: ἄτομος, romanized: *átomos*, lit.
[src:saga-orchestration/atomicity-database-systems] 'undividable') is the property of a database transaction consisting of an *indivisible* and *irreducible* series of database operations such that either *all* occur, or *none* occur.
[src:saga-orchestration/atomicity-database-systems] It is one of the ACID transaction properties: Atomicity, Consistency, Isolation, Durability.
[src:saga-orchestration/atomicity-database-systems] A guarantee of atomicity prevents partial database updates from occurring, because they can cause greater problems than rejecting the whole series outright.
[src:saga-orchestration/atomicity-database-systems] As a consequence, an **atomic transaction** cannot be observed to be in progress by another database client: at one moment in time, it has not yet happened, and at the next it has already occurred in whole (or nothing happened if the transaction was cancelled in progress).
[src:saga-orchestration/atomicity-database-systems] An example of transaction atomicity could be a digital monetary transfer from bank account A to account B.
[src:saga-orchestration/atomicity-database-systems] It consists of two operations, debiting the money from account A and crediting it to account B.
[src:saga-orchestration/atomicity-database-systems] Performing both of these operations inside of an atomic transaction ensures that the database remains in a consistent state, if either operation fails there will not be any unaccountable credits or debits affecting either account.
[src:saga-orchestration/atomicity-database-systems] Atomicity does not behave completely orthogonally with regard to the other ACID properties of transactions.
[src:saga-orchestration/atomicity-database-systems] For example, isolation relies on atomicity to roll back the enclosing transaction in the event of an isolation violation such as a deadlock; consistency also relies on atomicity to roll back the enclosing transaction in the event of a consistency violation by an illegal transaction.
[src:saga-orchestration/atomicity-database-systems] As a result of this, a failure to detect a violation and roll back the enclosing transaction may cause an isolation or consistency failure.
[src:saga-orchestration/atomicity-database-systems] Typically, systems implement Atomicity by providing some mechanism to indicate which transactions have started and which finished; or by keeping a copy of the data before any changes occurred (Read-copy-update).
[src:saga-orchestration/atomicity-database-systems] Several filesystems have developed methods for avoiding the need to keep multiple copies of data, using journaling (see journaling file system).
[src:saga-orchestration/atomicity-database-systems] Databases usually implement this using some form of logging/journaling to track changes.
[src:saga-orchestration/atomicity-database-systems] The system synchronizes the logs (often the metadata) as necessary after changes have successfully taken place.
[src:saga-orchestration/atomicity-database-systems] Afterwards, crash recovery ignores incomplete entries.
[src:saga-orchestration/atomicity-database-systems] Although implementations vary depending on factors such as concurrency issues, the principle of atomicity – i.e. complete success or complete failure – remain.
[src:saga-orchestration/atomicity-database-systems] Ultimately, any application-level implementation relies on operating-system functionality.
[src:saga-orchestration/atomicity-database-systems] At the file-system level, POSIX-compliant systems provide system calls such as `open(2)` and `flock(2)` that allow applications to atomically open or lock a file.
[src:saga-orchestration/atomicity-database-systems] At the process level, POSIX Threads provide adequate synchronization primitives.
[src:saga-orchestration/atomicity-database-systems] The hardware level requires atomic operations such as Test-and-set, Fetch-and-add, Compare-and-swap, or Load-Link/Store-Conditional, together with memory barriers.
[src:saga-orchestration/atomicity-database-systems] Portable operating systems cannot simply block interrupts to implement synchronization, since hardware that lacks concurrent execution such as hyper-threading or multi-processing is now extremely rare.
[src:saga-orchestration/atomicity-database-systems] In distributed and sharded databases, atomicity is complicated by network latency and the potential for partial failures.
[src:saga-orchestration/atomicity-database-systems] While traditional distributed systems often employ locking protocols (like 2PC) to ensure cross-shard atomicity, these can introduce performance bottlenecks.
[src:saga-orchestration/atomicity-database-systems] Recent research into distributed ledger consensus suggests alternative models, such as "braided synchronization".
[src:saga-orchestration/atomicity-database-systems] This technique, utilized in protocols like Cerberus, intertwines the consensus phases of multiple shards to enforce atomic guarantees without a global ordering of all transactions.
[src:saga-orchestration/compensating-transaction] In transaction processing and distributed computing, a **compensating transaction** is a transaction that reverses the effects of a previously committed transaction.
[src:saga-orchestration/compensating-transaction] It is a core concept in the saga design pattern, used to maintain data consistency across multiple services or databases in scenarios where traditional ACID transactions are not feasible or practical.
[src:saga-orchestration/compensating-transaction] A compensating transaction is necessary when a business process, which may consist of several individual transactions, fails after one or more of its steps have already been successfully completed (committed).
[src:saga-orchestration/compensating-transaction] Unlike a database rollback, which discards uncommitted changes, a compensating transaction is a new transaction that applies business logic to semantically undo the work of a completed transaction, thereby restoring the system to a consistent state.
[src:saga-orchestration/compensating-transaction] The execution of a business process often involves a series of operations that must be treated as a single atomic unit.
[src:saga-orchestration/compensating-transaction] While a traditional database transaction achieves this atomicity with commit and rollback mechanisms, this approach is often insufficient for complex, long-running processes.
[src:saga-orchestration/compensating-transaction] A compensating transaction works by executing an operation that is the logical inverse of the original operation.
[src:saga-orchestration/compensating-transaction] For example, if the original transaction was "debit account by $100," its compensating transaction would be "credit account by $100." Each step in a long-running process must have a corresponding compensating transaction designed.
[src:saga-orchestration/compensating-transaction] If the process fails at any point, the system executes the compensating transactions for all previously completed steps in reverse order to undo the process.
[src:saga-orchestration/compensating-transaction] Compensating transactions are a key pattern for maintaining consistency in distributed and complex systems.
[src:saga-orchestration/compensating-transaction] Compensating transactions are fundamental to the **saga pattern**.
[src:saga-orchestration/compensating-transaction] A saga is a sequence of local transactions where each transaction updates data within a single service and publishes an event.
[src:saga-orchestration/compensating-transaction] If a local transaction fails for any reason, the saga executes a series of compensating transactions to revert the changes made by the preceding local transactions.
[src:saga-orchestration/compensating-transaction] This pattern is essential for processes that are long-lived, such as a trip-booking process that involves coordinating flights, hotels, and car rentals.
[src:saga-orchestration/compensating-transaction] Because these operations might span a long period and involve multiple independent web services, holding database locks is impractical.
[src:saga-orchestration/compensating-transaction] Instead, each service commits its transaction and has a compensating transaction ready in case a subsequent step fails.
[src:saga-orchestration/compensating-transaction] This differs from distributed transactions using the two-phase-commit protocol, as it avoids locking resources for extended durations.
[src:saga-orchestration/compensating-transaction] In systems where a global commit/rollback mechanism is not available—such as those integrating legacy systems, third-party APIs, or non-transactional data stores—a failed operation must be undone manually.
[src:saga-orchestration/compensating-transaction] A compensating transaction provides a formal structure for this "undo" logic.
[src:saga-orchestration/compensating-transaction] In this context, the logic is a workaround that must be explicitly designed and implemented by the system architect, who must also plan for the possibility that the compensating transaction itself could fail.
[src:saga-orchestration/compensating-transaction] Compensating transactions are often designed into Web services that participate in business processes as part of a service-oriented architecture (SOA).
[src:saga-orchestration/compensating-transaction] Standards like Business Process Execution Language (BPEL) include provisions for defining compensation logic within a business process definition, allowing for the automated handling of failures in complex, multi-service interactions.
[src:saga-orchestration/compensating-transaction] Because of these challenges, compensating transactions do not guarantee a return to the exact original state but rather to a state that is semantically consistent from a business perspective.
[src:saga-orchestration/distributed-transaction] A **distributed transaction** operates within a distributed environment, typically involving multiple nodes across a network depending on the location of the data.
[src:saga-orchestration/distributed-transaction] A key aspect of distributed transactions is atomicity, which ensures that the transaction is completed in its entirety or not executed at all.
[src:saga-orchestration/distributed-transaction] It's essential to note that distributed transactions are not limited to databases.
[src:saga-orchestration/distributed-transaction] The Open Group, a vendor consortium, proposed the X/Open Distributed Transaction Processing Model (X/Open XA), which became a de facto standard for the behavior of transaction model components.
[src:saga-orchestration/distributed-transaction] Databases are common transactional resources and, often, transactions span a couple of such databases.
[src:saga-orchestration/distributed-transaction] In this case, a distributed transaction can be seen as a database transaction that must be synchronized (or provide ACID properties) among multiple participating databases which are distributed among different physical locations.
[src:saga-orchestration/distributed-transaction] The isolation property (the I of ACID) poses a special challenge for multi database transactions, since the (global) serializability property could be violated, even if each database provides it (see also global serializability).
[src:saga-orchestration/distributed-transaction] In practice most commercial database systems use strong strict two-phase locking (SS2PL) for concurrency control, which ensures global serializability, if all the participating databases employ it.
[src:saga-orchestration/distributed-transaction] A common algorithm for ensuring correct completion of a distributed transaction is the two-phase commit (2PC).
[src:saga-orchestration/distributed-transaction] This algorithm is usually applied for updates able to commit in a short period of time, ranging from couple of milliseconds to couple of minutes.
[src:saga-orchestration/distributed-transaction] There are also long-lived distributed transactions, for example a transaction to book a trip, which consists of booking a flight, a rental car and a hotel.
[src:saga-orchestration/distributed-transaction] Since booking the flight might take up to a day to get a confirmation, two-phase commit is not applicable here, it will lock the resources for this long.
[src:saga-orchestration/distributed-transaction] In this case more sophisticated techniques that involve multiple undo levels are used.
[src:saga-orchestration/distributed-transaction] The way you can undo the hotel booking by calling a desk and cancelling the reservation, a system can be designed to undo certain operations (unless they are irreversibly finished).
[src:saga-orchestration/distributed-transaction] In practice, long-lived distributed transactions are implemented in systems based on web services.
[src:saga-orchestration/distributed-transaction] Usually these transactions utilize principles of compensating transactions, Optimism and Isolation Without Locking.
[src:saga-orchestration/distributed-transaction] The X/Open standard does not cover long-lived distributed transactions.
[src:saga-orchestration/distributed-transaction] Several technologies, including Jakarta Enterprise Beans and Microsoft Transaction Server fully support distributed transaction standards.
[src:saga-orchestration/eventual-consistency] Eventually-consistent services are often classified as providing BASE semantics (basically-available, soft-state, eventual consistency), in contrast to traditional ACID (atomicity, consistency, isolation, durability).
[src:saga-orchestration/eventual-consistency] Eventual consistency faces criticism for adding complexity to distributed software applications.
[src:saga-orchestration/eventual-consistency] This complexity arises because eventual consistency provides only a liveness guarantee (ensuring reads eventually return the same value) without safety guarantees—allowing any intermediate value before convergence.
[src:saga-orchestration/eventual-consistency] Application developers find this challenging because it differs from single-threaded programming, where variables reliably return their assigned values immediately.
[src:saga-orchestration/eventual-consistency] With weak consistency guarantees, developers must carefully consider these limitations, as incorrect assumptions about consistency levels can lead to subtle bugs that only surface during network failures or high concurrency.
[src:saga-orchestration/eventual-consistency] In order to ensure replica convergence, a system must reconcile differences between multiple copies of distributed data.
[src:saga-orchestration/eventual-consistency] The most appropriate approach to reconciliation depends on the application.
[src:saga-orchestration/eventual-consistency] A widespread approach is "last writer wins".
[src:saga-orchestration/eventual-consistency] Another is to invoke a user-specified conflict handler.
[src:saga-orchestration/eventual-consistency] Timestamps and vector clocks are often used to detect concurrency between updates.
[src:saga-orchestration/eventual-consistency] Some people use "first writer wins" in situations where "last writer wins" is unacceptable.
[src:saga-orchestration/eventual-consistency] Whereas eventual consistency is only a liveness guarantee (updates will be observed eventually), **strong eventual consistency** (SEC) adds the safety guarantee that any two nodes that have received the same (unordered) set of updates will be in the same state.
[src:saga-orchestration/eventual-consistency] A common approach to ensure SEC is conflict-free replicated data types.
[src:saga-orchestration/microservices] In software engineering, a **microservice** architecture is an architectural pattern that organizes an application into a collection of loosely coupled, fine-grained services that communicate through lightweight protocols.
[src:saga-orchestration/microservices] This pattern allows teams to develop, deploy, and scale services independently, improving modularity, scalability, and adaptability.
[src:saga-orchestration/microservices] However, it introduces additional complexity, particularly in managing distributed systems and inter-service communication, making the initial implementation more challenging compared to a monolithic architecture.
[src:saga-orchestration/microservices] There is no single, universally agreed-upon definition of microservices.
[src:saga-orchestration/microservices] However, they are generally characterized by a focus on modularity, with each service designed around a specific business capability.
[src:saga-orchestration/microservices] These services are loosely coupled, independently deployable, and often developed and scaled separately, enabling greater flexibility and agility in managing complex systems.
[src:saga-orchestration/microservices] Microservices architecture is closely associated with principles such as domain-driven design, decentralization of data and governance, and the flexibility to use different technologies for individual services to best meet their requirements.
[src:saga-orchestration/microservices] It is common for microservices architectures to be adopted for cloud-native applications, serverless computing, and applications using lightweight container deployment via OS-level virtualization.
[src:saga-orchestration/microservices] According to Fowler, because of the large number (when compared to monolithic application implementations) of services, decentralized continuous delivery and DevOps with holistic service monitoring are necessary to effectively develop, maintain, and operate such applications.
[src:saga-orchestration/microservices] A consequence of (and rationale for) following this approach is that the individual microservices can be individually scaled.
[src:saga-orchestration/microservices] In the monolithic approach, an application supporting three functions would have to be scaled in its entirety even if only one of these functions had a resource constraint.
[src:saga-orchestration/microservices] With microservices, only the microservice supporting the function with resource constraints needs to be scaled out, thus providing resource and cost optimization benefits.
[src:saga-orchestration/microservices] Despite its benefits, microservices architecture introduces challenges such as increased operational complexity, network latency, and the need for robust monitoring and fault tolerance mechanisms.
[src:saga-orchestration/microservices] Cell-based architecture is a distributed computing design in which computational resources are organized into self-contained units called cells.
[src:saga-orchestration/microservices] Each cell operates independently, handling a subset of requests while maintaining scalability, fault isolation, and availability.
[src:saga-orchestration/microservices] A cell typically consists of multiple microservices and functions as an autonomous unit.
[src:saga-orchestration/microservices] In some implementations, entire sets of microservices are replicated across multiple cells, enabling requests to be rerouted to another operational cell if one experiences a failure.
[src:saga-orchestration/microservices] This approach is intended to improve system-wide resilience by limiting the impact of localized failures.
[src:saga-orchestration/microservices] Some implementations incorporate circuit breakers within and between cells.
[src:saga-orchestration/microservices] Within a cell, circuit breakers may be used to mitigate cascading failures among microservices, while inter-cell circuit breakers can isolate failing cells and redirect traffic to those that remain operational.
[src:saga-orchestration/microservices] Cell-based architecture has been adopted in certain large-scale distributed systems where fault isolation and redundancy are design priorities.
[src:saga-orchestration/microservices] Its implementation varies based on system requirements, infrastructure constraints, and specific operational goals.
[src:saga-orchestration/microservices] In 1999, software developer Peter Rodgers had been working on the Dexter research project at Hewlett Packard Labs, whose aim was to make code less brittle and to make large-scale, complex software systems robust to change.
[src:saga-orchestration/microservices] Ultimately this path of research led to the development of resource-oriented computing (ROC), a generalized computation abstraction in which REST is a special subset.
[src:saga-orchestration/microservices] In 2005, during a presentation at the Web Services Edge conference, Rodgers argued for "REST-services" and stated that "Software components are Micro-Web-Services...
[src:saga-orchestration/microservices] Micro-Services are composed using Unix-like pipelines (the Web meets Unix = true loose-coupling).
[src:saga-orchestration/microservices] Services can call services (+multiple language run-times).
[src:saga-orchestration/microservices] Complex service assemblies are abstracted behind simple URI interfaces.
[src:saga-orchestration/microservices] Also in 2005, Alistair Cockburn wrote about hexagonal architecture which is a software design pattern that is used along with the microservices.
[src:saga-orchestration/microservices] This pattern makes the design of the microservice possible since it isolates in layers the business logic from the auxiliary services needed in order to deploy and run the microservice completely independent from others.
[src:saga-orchestration/microservices] Determining the appropriate level of (micro)service granularity in a microservices architecture often requires iterative collaboration between architects and developers.
[src:saga-orchestration/microservices] This process involves evaluating user requirements, service responsibilities, and architectural characteristics, such as non-functional requirements.
[src:saga-orchestration/microservices] Neal Ford highlights the role of integrator and disintegrator factors in this context.
[src:saga-orchestration/microservices] Integrator factors, such as shared transactions or tightly coupled processes, favor combining services, while disintegrator factors, such as fault tolerance or independent scalability, encourage splitting services to meet operational and architectural goals.
[src:saga-orchestration/microservices] Additionally, fitness functions, as proposed by Neal Ford, can be used to validate architectural decisions and service granularity by continuously measuring system qualities or behaviors that are critical to stakeholders, ensuring alignment with overall architectural objectives.
[src:saga-orchestration/microservices] In microservices architectures, service granularity influences testing, deployment, performance, and reliability.
[src:saga-orchestration/microservices] Very fine-grained microservices are typically easier to test and deploy independently, but they often experience lower performance and reduced overall reliability due to increased interservice communication and more complex service choreography.
[src:saga-orchestration/microservices] Coarse-grained services exhibit contrasting characteristics.
[src:saga-orchestration/microservices] They generally provide higher robustness and reliability by minimizing communication overhead and coordination complexity, but they are more challenging to test and deploy because modifications affect a broader functional scope.
[src:saga-orchestration/microservices] The appropriate level of service granularity is determined by business drivers.
[src:saga-orchestration/microservices] Architectural decisions commonly begin with identifying these drivers and then aligning architectural characteristics such as performance, scalability, reliability, or deployment flexibility to support them.
[src:saga-orchestration/microservices] A bounded context, a fundamental concept in domain-driven design (DDD), defines a specific area within which a domain model is consistent and valid, ensuring clarity and separation of concerns.
[src:saga-orchestration/microservices] In microservices architecture, a bounded context often maps to a microservice, but this relationship can vary depending on the design approach.
[src:saga-orchestration/microservices] A one-to-one relationship, where each bounded context is implemented as a single microservice, is typically ideal as it maintains clear boundaries, reduces coupling, and enables independent deployment and scaling.
[src:saga-orchestration/microservices] The choice of relationship should balance the principles of DDD with the system's business goals, technical constraints, and operational requirements.
[src:saga-orchestration/microservices] The architecture introduces additional complexity and new problems to deal with, such as latency, message format design, backup/availability/consistency (BAC), load balancing and fault tolerance.
[src:saga-orchestration/microservices] All of these problems have to be addressed at scale.
[src:saga-orchestration/microservices] The complexity of a monolithic application does not disappear if it is re-implemented as a set of microservices.
[src:saga-orchestration/microservices] Some of the complexity gets translated into operational complexity.
[src:saga-orchestration/microservices] Other places where the complexity manifests itself are increased network traffic and slower performance.
[src:saga-orchestration/microservices] Also, an application made up of any number of microservices has a larger number of interface points to access its respective ecosystem, which increases the architectural complexity.
[src:saga-orchestration/microservices] Various organizing principles (such as hypermedia as the engine of application state (HATEOAS), interface and data model documentation captured via Swagger, etc.) have been applied to reduce the impact of such additional complexity.
[src:saga-orchestration/microservices] Microservices are susceptible to the fallacies of distributed computing – a series of misconceptions that can lead to significant issues in software development and deployment.
[src:saga-orchestration/microservices] Ideally, microservices follow a "share-nothing" architecture.
[src:saga-orchestration/microservices] However, in practice, microservices architectures often encounter situations where code must be shared across services.
[src:saga-orchestration/microservices] Each approach has its advantages and trade-offs, depending on the specific context and requirements.
[src:saga-orchestration/microservices] Richards & Ford in *Fundamentals of software architecture* (2020) propose each microservice should have its own architectural characteristics (a.k.a. non functional requirements), and architects should not define uniform characteristics for the entire distributed system.
[src:saga-orchestration/microservices] To avoid having to coordinate deployments across different microservices, Sam Newman suggests keeping the interfaces of microservices stable and making backwards-compatible changes as interfaces evolve.
[src:saga-orchestration/microservices] On the topic of testing, Newman in *Building Microservices* (2015) proposes consumer-driven contract testing as a better alternative to traditional end-to-end testing in the context of microservices.
[src:saga-orchestration/microservices] He also suggests the use of log aggregation and metrics aggregation as well as distributed tracing tools to ensure the observability of systems composed of microservices.
[src:saga-orchestration/microservices] Computer microservices can be implemented in different programming languages and might use different infrastructures.
[src:saga-orchestration/microservices] Therefore, the most important technology choices are the way microservices communicate with each other (synchronous, asynchronous, UI integration) and the protocols used for the communication (e.g.
[src:saga-orchestration/microservices] In a traditional system, most technology choices like the programming language impact the whole system.
[src:saga-orchestration/microservices] Therefore, the approach to choosing technologies is quite different.
[src:saga-orchestration/microservices] The Eclipse Foundation has published a specification for developing microservices, Eclipse MicroProfile.
[src:saga-orchestration/microservices] In a service mesh, each service instance is paired with an instance of a reverse proxy server, called a service proxy, sidecar proxy, or sidecar.
[src:saga-orchestration/microservices] The service instance and sidecar proxy share a container, and the containers are managed by a container orchestration tool such as Kubernetes, Docker Swarm, or DC/OS.
[src:saga-orchestration/microservices] The service proxies are responsible for communication with other service instances and can support capabilities such as service (instance) discovery, load balancing, authentication and authorization, secure communications, and others.
[src:saga-orchestration/two-phase-commit-protocol] In transaction processing, databases, and computer networking, the **two-phase commit protocol** (**2PC**, *tupac*) is a type of atomic commitment protocol (ACP).
[src:saga-orchestration/two-phase-commit-protocol] It is a distributed algorithm that coordinates all the processes that participate in a distributed atomic transaction on whether to commit or abort (roll back) the transaction.
[src:saga-orchestration/two-phase-commit-protocol] This protocol (a specialised type of consensus protocol) achieves its goal even in many cases of temporary system failure (involving either process, network node, communication, etc. failures), and is thus widely used.
[src:saga-orchestration/two-phase-commit-protocol] However, it is not resilient to all possible failure configurations, and in rare cases, manual intervention is needed to remedy an outcome.
[src:saga-orchestration/two-phase-commit-protocol] To accommodate recovery from failure (automatic in most cases) the protocol's participants use logging of the protocol's states.
[src:saga-orchestration/two-phase-commit-protocol] Log records, which are typically slow to generate but survive failures, are used by the protocol's recovery procedures.
[src:saga-orchestration/two-phase-commit-protocol] Many protocol variants exist that primarily differ in logging strategies and recovery mechanisms.
[src:saga-orchestration/two-phase-commit-protocol] Though usually intended to be used infrequently, recovery procedures compose a substantial portion of the protocol, due to many possible failure scenarios to be considered and supported by the protocol.
[src:saga-orchestration/two-phase-commit-protocol] The commit phase, in which, based on voting of the participants, the coordinator decides whether to commit (only if all have voted "Yes") or abort the transaction (otherwise), and notifies the result to all the participants.
[src:saga-orchestration/two-phase-commit-protocol] The participants then follow with the needed actions (commit or abort) with their local transactional resources (also called recoverable resources; e.g., database data) and their respective portions in the transaction's other output (if applicable).
[src:saga-orchestration/two-phase-commit-protocol] The two-phase commit (2PC) protocol should not be confused with the two-phase locking (2PL) protocol, a concurrency control protocol.
[src:saga-orchestration/two-phase-commit-protocol] The protocol works in the following manner: one node is a designated coordinator, which is the master site, and the rest of the nodes in the network are designated the participants.
[src:saga-orchestration/two-phase-commit-protocol] 4. any two nodes can communicate with each other.
[src:saga-orchestration/two-phase-commit-protocol] The last assumption is not too restrictive, as network communication can typically be rerouted.
[src:saga-orchestration/two-phase-commit-protocol] The first two assumptions are much stronger; if a node is totally destroyed then data can be lost.
[src:saga-orchestration/two-phase-commit-protocol] The protocol is initiated by the coordinator after the last step of the transaction has been reached.
[src:saga-orchestration/two-phase-commit-protocol] The participants then respond with an agreement message or an abort message depending on whether the transaction has been processed successfully at the participant.
[src:saga-orchestration/two-phase-commit-protocol] The participants execute the transaction up to the point where they will be asked to commit.
[src:saga-orchestration/two-phase-commit-protocol] They each write an entry to their undo log and an entry to their redo log.
[src:saga-orchestration/two-phase-commit-protocol] (participant votes No to commit), if the participant experiences a failure that will make it impossible to commit.
[src:saga-orchestration/two-phase-commit-protocol] Each participant completes the operation, and releases all the locks and resources held during the transaction.
[src:saga-orchestration/two-phase-commit-protocol] Each participant sends an acknowledgement to the coordinator.
[src:saga-orchestration/two-phase-commit-protocol] The coordinator completes the transaction when all acknowledgements have been received.
[src:saga-orchestration/two-phase-commit-protocol] Each participant undoes the transaction using the undo log, and releases the resources and locks held during the transaction.
[src:saga-orchestration/two-phase-commit-protocol] The coordinator undoes the transaction when all acknowledgements have been received.
[src:saga-orchestration/two-phase-commit-protocol] An * next to the record type means that the record is forced to stable storage.
[src:saga-orchestration/two-phase-commit-protocol] If the coordinator fails permanently, some participants will never resolve their transactions: After a participant has sent an agreement message as a response to the commit-request message from the coordinator, it will block until a commit or rollback is received.
[src:saga-orchestration/two-phase-commit-protocol] A two-phase commit protocol cannot dependably recover from a failure of both the coordinator and a cohort member during the commit phase.
[src:saga-orchestration/two-phase-commit-protocol] If only the coordinator had failed, and no cohort members had received a commit message, it could safely be inferred that no commit had happened.
[src:saga-orchestration/two-phase-commit-protocol] If, however, both the coordinator and a cohort member failed, it is possible that the failed cohort member was the first to be notified, and had actually done the commit.
[src:saga-orchestration/two-phase-commit-protocol] Even if a new coordinator is selected, it cannot confidently proceed with the operation until it has received an agreement from all cohort members, and hence must block until all cohort members respond.
[src:saga-orchestration/two-phase-commit-protocol] In many cases the 2PC protocol is distributed in a computer network.
[src:saga-orchestration/two-phase-commit-protocol] The databases involved with a distributed transaction, the participants, both the coordinator and participants, register to close TMs (typically residing on respective same network nodes as the participants) for terminating that transaction using 2PC.
[src:saga-orchestration/two-phase-commit-protocol] Each distributed transaction has an ad hoc set of TMs, the TMs to which the transaction participants register.
[src:saga-orchestration/two-phase-commit-protocol] A leader, the coordinator TM, exists for each transaction to coordinate 2PC for it, typically the TM of the coordinator database.
[src:saga-orchestration/two-phase-commit-protocol] However, the coordinator role can be transferred to another TM for performance or reliability reasons.
[src:saga-orchestration/two-phase-commit-protocol] Rather than exchanging 2PC messages among themselves, the participants exchange the messages with their respective TMs.
[src:saga-orchestration/two-phase-commit-protocol] The relevant TMs communicate among themselves to execute the 2PC protocol schema above, "representing" the respective participants, for terminating that transaction.
[src:saga-orchestration/two-phase-commit-protocol] With this architecture the protocol is fully distributed (does not need any central processing component or data structure), and scales up with number of network nodes (network size) effectively.
[src:saga-orchestration/two-phase-commit-protocol] This common architecture is also effective for the distribution of other atomic commitment protocols besides 2PC, since all such protocols use the same voting mechanism and outcome propagation to protocol participants.
[src:saga-orchestration/two-phase-commit-protocol] Database research has been done on ways to get most of the benefits of the two-phase commit protocol while reducing costs by protocol optimizations and protocol operations saving under certain system's behavior assumptions.
[src:saga-orchestration/two-phase-commit-protocol] Presumed abort or Presumed commit are common such optimizations.
[src:saga-orchestration/two-phase-commit-protocol] An assumption about the outcome of transactions, either commit, or abort, can save both messages and logging operations by the participants during the 2PC protocol's execution.
[src:saga-orchestration/two-phase-commit-protocol] For example, when presumed abort, if during system recovery from failure no logged evidence for commit of some transaction is found by the recovery procedure, then it assumes that the transaction has been aborted, and acts accordingly.
[src:saga-orchestration/two-phase-commit-protocol] This means that it does not matter if aborts are logged at all, and such logging can be saved under this assumption.
[src:saga-orchestration/two-phase-commit-protocol] Typically a penalty of additional operations is paid during recovery from failure, depending on optimization type.
[src:saga-orchestration/two-phase-commit-protocol] Thus the best variant of optimization, if any, is chosen according to failure and transaction outcome statistics.
[src:saga-orchestration/two-phase-commit-protocol] The Tree 2PC protocol (also called Nested 2PC, or Recursive 2PC) is a common variant of 2PC in a computer network, which better utilizes the underlying communication infrastructure.
[src:saga-orchestration/two-phase-commit-protocol] The participants in a distributed transaction are typically invoked in an order which defines a tree structure, the invocation tree, where the participants are the nodes and the edges are the invocations (communication links).
[src:saga-orchestration/two-phase-commit-protocol] The same tree is commonly utilized to complete the transaction by a 2PC protocol, but also another communication tree can be utilized for this, in principle.
[src:saga-orchestration/two-phase-commit-protocol] In a tree 2PC the coordinator is considered the root ("top") of a communication tree (inverted tree), while the participants are the other nodes.
[src:saga-orchestration/two-phase-commit-protocol] The coordinator can be the node that originated the transaction (invoked recursively (transitively) the other participants), but also another node in the same tree can take the coordinator role instead.
[src:saga-orchestration/two-phase-commit-protocol] The Dynamic two-phase commit (Dynamic two-phase commitment, D2PC) protocol is a variant of Tree 2PC with no predetermined coordinator.
[src:saga-orchestration/two-phase-commit-protocol] It subsumes several optimizations that have been proposed earlier.
[src:saga-orchestration/two-phase-commit-protocol] Agreement messages (Yes votes) start to propagate from all the leaves, each leaf when completing its tasks on behalf of the transaction (becoming ready).
[src:saga-orchestration/two-phase-commit-protocol] An intermediate (non leaf) node sends ready when an agreement message to the last (single) neighboring node from which agreement message has not yet been received.
[src:saga-orchestration/two-phase-commit-protocol] The coordinator is determined dynamically by racing agreement messages over the transaction tree, at the place where they collide.
[src:saga-orchestration/two-phase-commit-protocol] They collide either at a transaction tree node, to be the coordinator, or on a tree edge.
[src:saga-orchestration/two-phase-commit-protocol] In the latter case one of the two edge's nodes is elected as a coordinator (any node).
